-- Africa Economics pack: 5 longform posts focused on Ghana + ECOWAS.
-- Idempotent: inserts by slug if missing.

do $$
begin
  insert into news_posts (title, slug, body, status, published_at, category, summary, hero_image_url, hero_image_alt, hero_image_credit)
  select
    'Ghana’s macro reset: the hard work after the headline',
    'ghana-macro-reset-hard-work-after-the-headline',
    E'Ghana’s economic story in recent years has oscillated between crisis and cautious recovery. When the headlines fade, what matters is whether the country can convert a painful stabilisation phase into durable growth.\n\nA useful way to think about the “macro reset” is in three linked constraints: **fiscal credibility**, **inflation and currency stability**, and **growth that is not purely commodity-led**.\n\n## 1) Fiscal credibility is an asset—until it isn’t\nGhana’s challenge has not been a lack of ideas, but a lack of consistent execution across political cycles. The state’s role in the economy is large, the wage bill is politically sensitive, and public investment often arrives packaged with contingent liabilities.\n\nA credible fiscal path is not simply “spend less.” It requires:\n- **Better revenue quality**: broaden the base, reduce exemptions, and digitise compliance.\n- **Expenditure discipline**: hard ceilings that are enforced, not “targets” revised mid-year.\n- **Transparent quasi-fiscal risks**: state-owned enterprises, energy arrears, and guarantees should be brought onto a dashboard the public can see.\n\nThe brutal truth: investors and citizens do not judge policy announcements—they judge whether rules survive elections.\n\n## 2) Inflation and the currency are psychological as much as technical\nIn Ghana, the cedi is a national barometer. When it weakens, it reshapes expectations: firms reprice, households hedge, and informal indexation becomes normal. That makes disinflation harder.\n\nTo stabilise expectations, the country needs a repeatable playbook:\n- **Monetary policy that is predictable** (and communicates clearly)\n- **FX liquidity that is transparent** (so rumours do not become runs)\n- **A credible fiscal anchor** (so the central bank is not pulled into financing)\n\nThe mechanics matter, but credibility matters more. A country that convinces people the worst is over can reduce inflation faster than one that merely raises rates.\n\n## 3) Growth must move beyond “price-taking” commodities\nGhana’s commodity base—gold, cocoa, and oil—will remain central. But a “next chapter” requires that the country captures more value and builds competitive services.\n\nThe pragmatic growth agenda looks like this:\n- **Value addition where it’s realistic**: not every product can be processed competitively, but some can.\n- **Export services**: business services, fintech, logistics, and creative industries can scale with relatively low capital.\n- **SME productivity**: simplify formalisation, digitise permits, reduce time-to-comply.\n\n## 4) The quiet constraint: energy reliability and cost\nAny growth strategy that ignores power reliability is fantasy. The cost of self-provision (generators, downtime, spoilage) is a hidden tax on SMEs.\n\n## What to watch\nOver the next 12–24 months, the signal is not one number. It is whether Ghana can keep three things moving at once:\n- a stable fiscal path\n- falling inflation that sticks\n- reforms that raise private investment—not just public spending\n\n## A sober conclusion\nGhana is not short of talent or entrepreneurial energy. Its constraint is execution. If it can turn stabilisation into predictable rules—especially around fiscal discipline and energy sector liabilities—growth can recover without returning to the same cliff.\n\nCTA:\nFor platforms like LocalLink, a more stable macro environment is not abstract. It reduces payment risk, increases repeat hiring, and makes trust-based digital work markets viable at scale.',
    'published',
    now() - interval '2 days',
    'Africa Economics',
    'After stabilisation comes the real test: fiscal credibility, sticky disinflation, and growth beyond commodities.',
    'https://images.pexels.com/photos/9879938/pexels-photo-9879938.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1600',
    'Professional at work',
    'Image: Pexels (free license).'
  where not exists (select 1 from news_posts where slug = 'ghana-macro-reset-hard-work-after-the-headline' and deleted_at is null);

  insert into news_posts (title, slug, body, status, published_at, category, summary, hero_image_url, hero_image_alt, hero_image_credit)
  select
    'ECOWAS trade is underbuilt infrastructure: the economics of “moving things”',
    'ecowas-trade-underbuilt-infrastructure-economics-of-moving-things',
    E'West Africa does not suffer from a shortage of demand. It suffers from a shortage of **reliable movement**.\n\nAcross ECOWAS, trade costs remain high not because goods do not exist, but because the region’s logistics chain is inconsistent: ports, corridors, checkpoints, warehousing, cold chains, and last-mile delivery.\n\n## 1) The real tariff is time\nFormal tariffs matter less than delays.\n\nA truck that spends hours at borders and checkpoints is effectively paying a tax in:\n- fuel\n- spoilage\n- driver time\n- lost inventory turns\n- bribes and informal fees\n\nThese costs are passed to consumers as high prices and volatile availability.\n\n## 2) Border friction is a design choice\nMany ECOWAS states have signed protocols on free movement of goods and people. The gap is enforcement.\n\nThe region’s problem is not lack of agreements, but:\n- fragmented digitisation of customs\n- inconsistent rules at sub-national checkpoints\n- weak interoperability of documents\n\n## 3) Ports are gateways—and bottlenecks\nPorts like Tema and Abidjan are modernising, but the surrounding systems often lag:\n- hinterland trucking capacity\n- storage and container turnaround\n- predictable clearance processes\n\nWhen port performance improves, the gains compound. When it stalls, the whole economy pays.\n\n## 4) Cold chains are the missing link for food markets\nFor produce and perishables, cold chains are not a luxury. They convert “seasonal abundance” into stable supply.\n\nWithout cold chains:\n- farmers accept distress prices\n- retailers face high wastage\n- consumers face volatile food inflation\n\n## 5) The private sector will build logistics—if rules are predictable\nInvestors build warehousing, fleets, and routing software when:\n- permits are transparent\n- enforcement is consistent\n- payments are reliable\n\nThis is where digital platforms help: they create traceability, dispute resolution, and performance history.\n\n## What would change the game\nThree interventions outperform dozens of speeches:\n- **end-to-end digital clearance** with interoperability\n- **checkpoint discipline** (fewer stops, published rules)\n- **corridor performance metrics** (publish transit time and cost)\n\n## Conclusion\nThe economics of ECOWAS trade is the economics of friction. If the region reduces logistics uncertainty, investment rises, food markets stabilise, and firms stop holding cash “just in case.”\n\nCTA:\nLocalLink’s approach—verification, escrow, and workflow history—applies to logistics too: reliability is the product.',
    'published',
    now() - interval '36 hours',
    'Africa Economics',
    'Trade barriers in West Africa are often invisible: time, uncertainty, and logistics friction.',
    'https://images.pexels.com/photos/19926733/pexels-photo-19926733.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1600',
    'Worker near stacked shipping containers in a warehouse',
    'Image: Pexels (free license).'
  where not exists (select 1 from news_posts where slug = 'ecowas-trade-underbuilt-infrastructure-economics-of-moving-things' and deleted_at is null);

  insert into news_posts (title, slug, body, status, published_at, category, summary, hero_image_url, hero_image_alt, hero_image_credit)
  select
    'Cocoa, gold, oil: Ghana’s commodity triangle and the growth trap',
    'ghana-commodities-triangle-cocoa-gold-oil-growth-trap',
    E'Ghana is blessed with commodities—and burdened by them.\n\nCommodities finance imports, stabilise government revenues in good years, and create large employment ecosystems. They also produce a familiar trap: when prices rise, reform slows; when prices fall, the adjustment is brutal.\n\n## Cocoa: value, volatility, and the temptation of “one big fix”\nCocoa is not just an export. It is a rural livelihoods system.\n\nThe practical issues are rarely solved by slogans:\n- farm productivity and replanting cycles\n- disease pressure and climate stress\n- input quality and extension services\n- incentives that reach the farm gate\n\nValue addition is important, but it is not automatic. Processing works when logistics, energy cost, and reliability make the economics viable.\n\n## Gold: the governance problem wearing a shiny suit\nGold is Ghana’s most important FX earner in many years. It is also where governance failures become visible:\n- environmental damage\n- informality and smuggling\n- conflict over land and permits\n\nA tough but necessary distinction:\n- artisanal mining that can be formalised\n- predatory extraction that destroys water and farmland\n\nThe state’s job is to set a credible regime: permits, enforcement, and incentives to bring production into a taxed, auditable system.\n\n## Oil and gas: smaller than people think, but politically louder\nOil revenue often arrives with political expectations it cannot satisfy.\n\nThe “resource curse” is not fate; it’s a budget problem. The solution is boring:\n- transparent rules\n- stabilisation funds that survive elections\n- investment in broad productivity, not prestige projects\n\n## The growth escape route: productivity + exports\nGhana’s long-term advantage is not just digging and shipping. It is building firms that can export:\n- processed foods where viable\n- business services\n- logistics and fintech\n- light manufacturing niches\n\nThe common constraint across all of them is reliability: power, policy consistency, and payment enforcement.\n\n## Conclusion\nCommodities will remain central, but Ghana’s next growth phase depends on building a non-commodity engine. The real test is whether reforms continue when prices are rising.\n\nCTA:\nTrust infrastructure—verification, escrow, dispute systems—helps convert informal markets into repeatable economic relationships. That is what growth looks like on the ground.',
    'published',
    now() - interval '30 hours',
    'Africa Economics',
    'Ghana’s commodities fund the economy—and repeatedly delay the reforms needed for broad productivity growth.',
    'https://images.pexels.com/photos/4792521/pexels-photo-4792521.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1600',
    'Worker fixing electrical wiring',
    'Image: Pexels (free license).'
  where not exists (select 1 from news_posts where slug = 'ghana-commodities-triangle-cocoa-gold-oil-growth-trap' and deleted_at is null);

  insert into news_posts (title, slug, body, status, published_at, category, summary, hero_image_url, hero_image_alt, hero_image_credit)
  select
    'The ECOWAS “Eco” currency: why the politics is harder than the economics',
    'ecowas-eco-currency-politics-harder-than-economics',
    E'A single currency is often sold as a shortcut to prosperity. In reality it is a commitment device: it trades national policy flexibility for regional stability.\n\nECOWAS has long discussed a common currency (“Eco”). The sticking points are not mysterious—they are structural.\n\n## 1) Currency unions require fiscal discipline\nA shared currency cannot survive if members run persistent deficits without credible enforcement.\n\nThe first question is not “what will it be called?” but:\n- who enforces the rules?\n- what happens when a member violates them?\n- who pays during asymmetric shocks?\n\n## 2) Asymmetric shocks are the norm in West Africa\nCommodity exposure differs across countries. Political cycles differ. Security shocks differ.\n\nA currency union works when:\n- labour and capital can move\n- fiscal transfers exist\n- banking supervision is unified\n\nECOWAS is still building these foundations.\n\n## 3) Trust is institutional\nMarkets believe institutions when they have:\n- clear mandates\n- operational independence\n- transparent decision-making\n- consistent enforcement\n\nWithout that, a currency union can become a mechanism for importing instability.\n\n## 4) What a realistic pathway looks like\nInstead of “big bang” monetary union, ECOWAS can win faster by building the plumbing:\n- payment interoperability\n- harmonised trade documentation\n- cross-border banking supervision cooperation\n- credible inflation and deficit anchors domestically\n\nThe paradox: doing the unglamorous work makes the glamorous project feasible.\n\n## Conclusion\nA common currency is not impossible—but it is not a branding exercise. It is an institutional project that demands discipline, credible enforcement, and political maturity.\n\nCTA:\nDigital work and payment platforms benefit most from what the Eco *would* symbolise: predictable rules and low-friction transactions across borders.',
    'published',
    now() - interval '24 hours',
    'Africa Economics',
    'A single currency is a governance project first. Without shared discipline and institutions, the benefits won’t stick.',
    'https://images.pexels.com/photos/7567536/pexels-photo-7567536.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1600',
    'Phone showing financial chart',
    'Image: Pexels (free license).'
  where not exists (select 1 from news_posts where slug = 'ecowas-eco-currency-politics-harder-than-economics' and deleted_at is null);

  insert into news_posts (title, slug, body, status, published_at, category, summary, hero_image_url, hero_image_alt, hero_image_credit)
  select
    'Power, prices, and productivity: why energy is Ghana’s most underrated economic variable',
    'power-prices-productivity-energy-ghana-underrated-variable',
    E'If you want a single variable that predicts SME growth, job creation, and competitiveness in Ghana, it is not a subsidy or a slogan. It is **reliable, affordable power**.\n\n## 1) Energy reliability is a hidden tax\nWhen power is unreliable, firms pay twice:\n- once through tariffs\n- again through self-provision (generators, maintenance, downtime)\n\nFor small firms, the second cost is often larger.\n\n## 2) Pricing must reflect reality—without killing SMEs\nEnergy pricing is politically sensitive. But underpricing creates arrears, maintenance backlog, and eventual crises.\n\nA “good” system:\n- targets support to the most vulnerable\n- prices predictably\n- invests in reliability\n\nA “bad” system:\n- hides costs until the system breaks\n\n## 3) Gas constraints shape electricity constraints\nGhana’s electricity reliability is tightly linked to gas supply and infrastructure. When gas is constrained, the system falls back to more expensive sources.\n\n## 4) The regional angle: West Africa Power Pool\nRegional interconnection can smooth shocks, but only if:\n- contracts are enforced\n- payment risk is managed\n- transmission constraints are addressed\n\n## 5) What would move the needle\nA practical agenda:\n- reduce technical and commercial losses\n- invest in maintenance that prevents failures\n- enforce payment discipline (including public sector arrears)\n- scale distributed solutions where the grid is weak\n\n## Conclusion\nEnergy is not a “sector.” It is the platform on which every other sector runs. If Ghana improves reliability and cost predictability, productivity rises without needing heroic policy experiments.\n\nCTA:\nPlatforms that organise work—like LocalLink—benefit when firms can plan. Reliability reduces disputes, missed appointments, and payment delays.',
    'published',
    now() - interval '18 hours',
    'Africa Economics',
    'Reliable, affordable electricity is a competitiveness strategy—especially for SMEs and the informal economy.',
    'https://images.pexels.com/photos/8853502/pexels-photo-8853502.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1600',
    'Technician working on solar panels',
    'Image: Pexels (free license).'
  where not exists (select 1 from news_posts where slug = 'power-prices-productivity-energy-ghana-underrated-variable' and deleted_at is null);
end $$;

